# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: humanities
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer was educated at Eton College and the University of Oxford, after which he studied the philosophy of logical positivism at the University of Vienna.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] From 1933 to 1940 he lectured on philosophy at Christ Church, Oxford.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] During the Second World War Ayer was a Special Operations Executive and MI6 agent.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer was Grote Professor of the Philosophy of Mind and Logic at University College London from 1946 until 1959, after which he returned to Oxford to become Wykeham Professor of Logic at New College.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He was president of the Aristotelian Society from 1951 to 1952 and knighted in 1970.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He was known for his advocacy of humanism, and was the second president of the British Humanist Association (now known as Humanists UK).
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer was born in St John's Wood, in north west London, to Jules Louis Cyprien Ayer and Reine (née Citroen), wealthy parents from continental Europe.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] His mother was from the Dutch-Jewish family that founded the Citroën car company in France; his father was a Swiss Calvinist financier who worked for the Rothschild family, including for their bank and as secretary to Alfred Rothschild.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer was educated at Ascham St Vincent's School, a former boarding preparatory school for boys in the seaside town of Eastbourne in Sussex, where he started boarding at the relatively early age of seven for reasons to do with the First World War, and at Eton College, where he was a King's Scholar.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] At Eton, Ayer first became known for his characteristic bravado and precocity.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Though primarily interested in his intellectual pursuits, he was very keen on sports, particularly rugby, and reputedly played the Eton Wall Game very well.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] In the final examinations at Eton, Ayer came second in his year, and first in classics.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] In his final year, as a member of Eton's senior council, he unsuccessfully campaigned for the abolition of corporal punishment at the school.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He won a classics scholarship to Christ Church, Oxford.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He graduated with a BA with first-class honours.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] After graduating from Oxford, Ayer spent a year in Vienna, returned to England and published his first book, *Language, Truth and Logic*, in 1936.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] This first exposition in English of logical positivism as newly developed by the Vienna Circle, made Ayer at age 26 the *enfant terrible* of British philosophy.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] As a newly famous intellectual, he played a prominent role in the Oxford by-election campaign of 1938.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer campaigned first for the Labour candidate Patrick Gordon Walker, and then for the joint Labour-Liberal "Independent Progressive" candidate Sandie Lindsay, who ran on an anti-appeasement platform against the Conservative candidate, Quintin Hogg, who ran as the appeasement candidate.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] The by-election, held on 27 October 1938, was quite close, with Hogg winning narrowly.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] In the Second World War, Ayer served as an officer in the Welsh Guards, chiefly in intelligence (Special Operations Executive (SOE) and MI6).
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He was commissioned as a second lieutenant into the Welsh Guards from the Officer Cadet Training Unit on 21 September 1940.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] After the war, Ayer briefly returned to the University of Oxford where he became a fellow and Dean of Wadham College.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He then taught philosophy at University College London from 1946 until 1959, during which time he started to appear on radio and television.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He was an extrovert and social mixer who liked dancing and attending clubs in London and New York.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He was also obsessed with sport: he had played rugby for Eton, and was a noted cricketer and a keen supporter of Tottenham Hotspur football team, where he was for many years a season ticket holder.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] For an academic, Ayer was an unusually well-connected figure in his time, with close links to 'high society' and the establishment.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Presiding over Oxford high-tables, he is often described as charming, but could also be intimidating.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer was married four times to three women.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] His first marriage was from 1932 to 1941, to (Grace Isabel) Renée, with whom he had a son – allegedly the son of Ayer's friend and colleague Stuart Hampshire – and a daughter.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] In 1960, Ayer married Alberta Constance (Dee) Wells, with whom he had one son.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] That marriage was dissolved in 1983, and the same year, Ayer married Vanessa Salmon, the former wife of politician Nigel Lawson.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] She died in 1985, and in 1989 Ayer remarried Wells, who survived him.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He also had a daughter with Hollywood columnist Sheilah Graham Westbrook.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] In 1950, Ayer attended the founding meeting of the Congress for Cultural Freedom in West Berlin, though he later said he went only because of the offer of a "free trip".
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He gave a speech on why John Stuart Mill's conceptions of liberty and freedom were still valid in the 20th century.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Together with the historian Hugh Trevor-Roper, Ayer fought against Arthur Koestler and Franz Borkenau, arguing that they were far too dogmatic and extreme in their anti-communism, in fact proposing illiberal measures in the defence of liberty.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Adding to the tension was the location of the congress in West Berlin, together with the fact that the Korean War began on 25 June 1950, the fourth day of the congress, giving a feeling that the world was on the brink of war.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] From 1959 to his retirement in 1978, Ayer held the Wykeham Chair, Professor of Logic at Oxford.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] After his retirement, Ayer taught or lectured several times in the United States, including as a visiting professor at Bard College in 1987.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] At a party that same year held by fashion designer Fernando Sanchez, Ayer confronted Mike Tyson, who was forcing himself upon the then little-known model Naomi Campbell.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] When Ayer demanded that Tyson stop, Tyson reportedly asked, "Do you know who the fuck I am?
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] I'm the heavyweight champion of the world", to which Ayer replied, "And I am the former Wykeham Professor of Logic.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] I suggest that we talk about this like rational men".
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer and Tyson then began to talk, allowing Campbell to slip out.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Gully Wells, Ayer's stepdaughter via Dee Wells, records the same event with some slight variation of detail.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer was also involved in politics, including anti-Vietnam War activism, supporting the Labour Party (and later the Social Democratic Party), chairing the Campaign Against Racial Discrimination in Sport, and serving as president of the Homosexual Law Reform Society.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] In 1978 he was interviewed for Bryan Magee's *Men of Ideas* television show, where he spoke about logical positivism and its legacy, later in 1987 he appeared on Magee's *The Great Philosophers* in an episode centering on Frege, Russell and Modern Logic.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] In 1988, a year before his death, Ayer wrote an article titled "What I saw when I was dead", describing an unusual near-death experience after his heart stopped for four minutes as he choked on smoked salmon.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] From 1980 to 1989 he lived at 51 York Street, Marylebone, where a memorial plaque was unveiled on 19 November 1995.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] In *Language, Truth and Logic* (1936), Ayer presents the verification principle as the only valid basis for philosophy.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Unless logical or empirical verification is possible, statements like "God exists" or "charity is good" are not true or untrue but meaningless, and may thus be excluded or ignored.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Religious language in particular is unverifiable and as such literally nonsense.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Mace's opinion that metaphysics is a form of intellectual poetry.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] The stance that a belief in God denotes no verifiable hypothesis is sometimes referred to as igtheism (for example, by Paul Kurtz).
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] In later years, Ayer reiterated that he did not believe in God and began to call himself an atheist.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He followed in the footsteps of Bertrand Russell by debating religion with the Jesuit scholar Frederick Copleston.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He focuses on propositions of the first class – moral judgements – saying that those of the second class belong to science, those of the third are mere commands, and those of the fourth (which are considered normative ethics as opposed to meta-ethics) are too concrete for ethical philosophy.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer argues that moral judgements cannot be translated into non-ethical, empirical terms and thus cannot be verified; in this he agrees with ethical intuitionists.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] But he differs from intuitionists by discarding appeals to intuition of non-empirical moral truths as "worthless" since the intuition of one person often contradicts that of another.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Between 1945 and 1947, together with Russell and George Orwell, Ayer contributed a series of articles to *Polemic*, a short-lived British *Magazine of Philosophy, Psychology, and Aesthetics* edited by the ex-Communist Humphrey Slater.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer was closely associated with the British humanist movement.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He was an Honorary Associate of the Rationalist Press Association from 1947 until his death.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He was elected a Foreign Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1963.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] In 1965, he became the first president of the Agnostics' Adoption Society and in the same year succeeded Julian Huxley as president of the British Humanist Association, a post he held until 1970.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] In 1968 he edited *The Humanist Outlook*, a collection of essays on the meaning of humanism.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He was one of the signers of the Humanist Manifesto.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer is best known for popularising the verification principle, in particular through his presentation of it in *Language, Truth, and Logic*.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] The principle was at the time at the heart of the debates of the so-called Vienna Circle, which Ayer had visited as a young guest.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Others, including the circle's leading light, Moritz Schlick, were already writing papers on the issue.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer's formulation was that a sentence can be meaningful only if it has verifiable empirical import; otherwise, it is either "analytical" if tautologous or "metaphysical" (i.e. meaningless, or "literally senseless").
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He started to work on the book at the age of 23 and it was published when he was 26.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer's philosophical ideas were deeply influenced by those of the Vienna Circle and David Hume.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] His clear, vibrant and polemical exposition of them makes *Language, Truth and Logic* essential reading on the tenets of logical empiricism; the book is regarded as a classic of 20th-century analytic philosophy and is widely read in philosophy courses around the world.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer wrote two books on the philosopher Bertrand Russell, *Russell and Moore: The Analytic Heritage* (1971) and *Russell* (1972).
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He also wrote an introductory book on the philosophy of David Hume and a short biography of Voltaire.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer was a strong critic of the German philosopher Martin Heidegger.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] As a logical positivist, Ayer was in conflict with Heidegger's vast, overarching theories of existence.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer considered them completely unverifiable through empirical demonstration and logical analysis, and this sort of philosophy an unfortunate strain in modern thought.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He considered Heidegger the worst example of such philosophy, which Ayer believed entirely useless.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] In *Philosophy in the Twentieth Century*, Ayer accuses Heidegger of "surprising ignorance" or "unscrupulous distortion" and "what can fairly be described as charlatanism".
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] In 1972–73, Ayer gave the Gifford Lectures at the University of St Andrews, later published as *The Central Questions of Philosophy*.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] He still believed in the viewpoint he shared with the logical positivists: that large parts of what was traditionally called philosophy—including metaphysics, theology and aesthetics—were not matters that could be judged true or false, and that it was thus meaningless to discuss them.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] In *The Concept of a Person and Other Essays* (1963), Ayer heavily criticised Wittgenstein's private language argument.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer's sense-data theory in *Foundations of Empirical Knowledge* was famously criticised by fellow Oxonian J.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Austin in *Sense and Sensibilia*, a landmark 1950s work of ordinary language philosophy.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer responded in the essay "Has Austin Refuted the Sense-datum Theory?", which can be found in his *Metaphysics and Common Sense* (1969).
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer was awarded a knighthood as Knight Bachelor in the London Gazette on 1 January 1970.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] Ayer's biographer, Ben Rogers, deposited 7 boxes of research material accumulated through the writing process at University College London in 2007.
[src:humanities/a-j-ayer] The material was donated in collaboration with Ayer's family.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Abductive reasoning, unlike deductive reasoning, yields a plausible conclusion but does not definitively verify it.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Abductive conclusions do not eliminate uncertainty or doubt, which is expressed in terms such as "best available" or "most likely".
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] While inductive reasoning draws general conclusions that apply to many situations, abductive conclusions are confined to the particular observations in question.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In the 1990s, as computing power grew, the fields of law, computer science, and artificial intelligence research spurred renewed interest in the subject of abduction.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Diagnostic expert systems frequently employ abduction.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning allows deriving b from a only where b is a formal logical consequence of a .
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In other words, deduction derives the consequences of the assumed.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Given the truth of the assumptions, a valid deduction guarantees the truth of the conclusion.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] For example, given that "Socrates is a man" ( $a_{1}$ ) and "All men are mortal" ( $a_{2}$ ), it follows that "Socrates is mortal" ( b ).
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Inductive reasoning is the process of inferring some *general* principle b from a body of knowledge a , where b does not necessarily follow from a . a might give us very good reason to accept b but does not ensure b .
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] For example, if all swans that a person has observed so far are white, they may infer a universal categorical proposition of the form *All swans are white*.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] They have good reason to believe the conclusion from the premise because it is the *best explanation* for their observations, but the truth of the conclusion is not guaranteed.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Indeed, it turns out that some swans are black.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Abductive reasoning allows inferring a as an explanation of b .
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] As a result of this inference, abduction allows the precondition a to be abducted from the consequence b .
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning and abductive reasoning differ in which end, left or right, of the proposition " a entails b " serves as the conclusion.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] For example, with deductive reasoning, knowing that it rained heavily during the night, you could deduce that the lawn will be wet in the morning without looking outside.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] With abductive reasoning, a couple leaving their house in the morning and seeing that their lawn is wet might abduce that it rained while they were asleep.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] This serves as a hypothesis that "best explains" their observation.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Given the many possible explanations for the lawn getting wet, their abduction does not establish certainty that it rained overnight, but it is still useful and can serve to orient them in their surroundings.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Despite many possible explanations for any physical process we observe, we tend to abduce a single explanation (or a few) for this process in the expectation that we can better orient ourselves in our surroundings and disregard some possibilities.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Properly used, abductive reasoning can be a useful source of priors in Bayesian statistics.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] One can understand abductive reasoning as inference to the best explanation, although the terms *abduction* and *inference to the best explanation* are not always used equivalently.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In logic, explanation is accomplished through the use of a logical theory T representing a domain and a set of observations O .
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is the process of deriving a set of explanations of O according to T and picking out one of those explanations.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In formal logic, O and E are assumed to be sets of literals.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Among the possible explanations E satisfying these two conditions, some other condition of minimality is usually imposed to avoid irrelevant facts (not contributing to the entailment of O ) being included in the explanations.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is then the process that picks out some member of E .
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Criteria for picking out a member representing "the best" explanation include the simplicity, the prior probability, or the explanatory power of the explanation.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] A proof-theoretical abduction method for first-order classical logic based on the sequent calculus and a dual one, based on semantic tableaux (analytic tableaux) have been proposed.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The methods are sound and complete and work for full first-order logic, without requiring any preliminary reduction of formulae into normal forms.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] These methods have also been extended to modal logic.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Abductive logic programming is a computational framework that extends normal logic programming with abduction.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] It separates the theory T into two components, one of which is a normal logic program, used to generate E by means of backward reasoning, the other of which is a set of integrity constraints, used to filter the set of candidate explanations.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] A different formalization of abduction is based on inverting the function that calculates the visible effects of the hypotheses.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Formally, we are given a set of hypotheses H and a set of manifestations M ; they are related by the domain knowledge, represented by a function e that takes as an argument a set of hypotheses and gives as a result the corresponding set of manifestations.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In other words, for every subset of the hypotheses $H'\subseteq H$ , their effects are known to be $e(H')$ .
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is performed by finding a set $H'\subseteq H$ such that $M\subseteq e(H')$ .
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In other words, abduction is performed by finding a set of hypotheses $H'$ such that their effects $e(H')$ include all observations M .
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] A common assumption is that the effects of the hypotheses are independent, that is, for every $H'\subseteq H$ , it holds that $e(H')=\bigcup _{h\in H'}e(\{h\})$ .
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] If this condition is met, abduction can be seen as a form of set covering.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Abductive validation is the process of validating a given hypothesis through abductive reasoning.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] This can also be called reasoning through successive approximation.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Under this principle, an explanation is valid if it is the best possible explanation of a set of known data.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The best possible explanation is often defined in terms of simplicity and elegance (see Occam's razor).
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Subjective logic generalises probabilistic logic by including degrees of epistemic uncertainty in the input arguments, i.e. instead of probabilities, the analyst can express arguments as subjective opinions.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Abduction in subjective logic is thus a generalization of probabilistic abduction described above.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The input arguments in subjective logic are subjective opinions which can be binomial when the opinion applies to a binary variable or multinomial when it applies to an *n*-ary variable.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Assume the domains $\mathbf {X}$ and $\mathbf {Y}$ with respective variables X and Y , the set of conditional opinions $\omega _{X\mid Y}$ (i.e. one conditional opinion for each value y ), and the base rate distribution $a_{Y}$ .
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Using these inverted conditionals together with the opinion $\omega _{X}$ subjective deduction denoted by the operator $\circledcirc$ can be used to abduce the marginal opinion $\omega _{Y\,{\overline {\|}}\,X}$ .
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The symbolic notation for subjective abduction is " ${\widetilde {\|}}$ ", and the operator itself is denoted as " ${\widetilde {\circledcirc }}$ ".
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The operator for the subjective Bayes' theorem is denoted " ${\widetilde {\phi \,}}$ ", and subjective deduction is denoted " $\circledcirc$ ".
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The advantage of using subjective logic abduction compared to probabilistic abduction is that both aleatoric and epistemic uncertainty about the input argument probabilities can be explicitly expressed and taken into account during the analysis.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] It is thus possible to perform abductive analysis in the presence of uncertain arguments, which naturally results in degrees of uncertainty in the output conclusions.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The idea that the simplest, most easily verifiable solution should be preferred over its more complicated counterparts is a very old one.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] To this point, George Pólya, in his treatise on problem-solving, makes reference to the following Latin truism: *simplex sigillum veri* (simplicity is the seal of truth).
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The American philosopher Charles Sanders Peirce introduced abduction into modern logic.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Over the years he called such inference *hypothesis*, *abduction*, *presumption*, and *retroduction*.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] He considered it a topic in logic as a normative field in philosophy, not in purely formal or mathematical logic, and eventually as a topic also in economics of research.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] As two stages of the development, extension, etc., of a hypothesis in scientific inquiry, abduction and also induction are often collapsed into one overarching concept—the hypothesis.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] That is why, in the scientific method known from Galileo and Bacon, the abductive stage of hypothesis formation is conceptualized simply as induction.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Thus, in the twentieth century this collapse was reinforced by Karl Popper's explication of the hypothetico-deductive model, where the hypothesis is considered to be just "a guess" (in the spirit of Peirce).
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] However, when the formation of a hypothesis is considered the result of a process it becomes clear that this "guess" has already been tried and made more robust in thought as a necessary stage of its acquiring the status of hypothesis.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Indeed, many abductions are rejected or heavily modified by subsequent abductions before they ever reach this stage.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Before 1900, Peirce treated abduction as the use of a known rule to explain an observation.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] For instance: it is a known rule that, if it rains, grass gets wet; so, to explain the fact that the grass on this lawn is wet, one *abduces* that it has rained.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Abduction can lead to false conclusions if other rules that might explain the observation are not taken into account—e.g. the grass could be wet from dew.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] This remains the common use of the term "abduction" in the social sciences and in artificial intelligence.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Peirce consistently characterized it as the kind of inference that originates a hypothesis by concluding in an explanation, though an unassured one, for some very curious or surprising (anomalous) observation stated in a premise.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] As early as 1865 he wrote that all conceptions of cause and force are reached through hypothetical inference; in the 1900s he wrote that all explanatory content of theories is reached through abduction.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In other respects Peirce revised his view of abduction over the years.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In Peirce's *On the Natural Classification of Arguments* (1867), hypothetical inference always deals with a cluster of characters (call them *P′, P′′, P′′′,* etc.) known to occur at least whenever a certain character (*M*) occurs.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Note that categorical syllogisms have elements traditionally called middles, predicates, and subjects.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] For example: All *men* [middle] are *mortal* [predicate]; *Socrates* [subject] is a *man* [middle]; ergo *Socrates* [subject] is *mortal* [predicate]".
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Below, 'M' stands for a middle; 'P' for a predicate; 'S' for a subject.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Peirce held that all deduction can be put into the form of the categorical syllogism Barbara (AAA-1).
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In 1878, in *Deduction, Induction, and Hypothesis*, there is no longer a need for multiple characters or predicates in order for an inference to be hypothetical, although it is still helpful.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Moreover, Peirce no longer poses hypothetical inference as concluding in a *probable* hypothesis.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In the forms themselves, it is understood but not explicit that induction involves random selection and that hypothetical inference involves response to a "very curious circumstance".
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The forms instead emphasize the modes of inference as rearrangements of one another's propositions (without the bracketed hints shown below).
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Peirce long treated abduction in terms of induction from characters or traits (weighed, not counted like objects), explicitly so in his influential 1883 "A theory of probable inference", in which he returns to involving probability in the hypothetical conclusion.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Like *Deduction, Induction, and Hypothesis* in 1878, it was widely read (see the historical books on statistics by Stephen Stigler), unlike his later amendments of his conception of abduction.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Today abduction remains most commonly understood as induction from characters and extension of a known rule to cover unexplained circumstances.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Sherlock Holmes used this method of reasoning in the stories of Arthur Conan Doyle, although Holmes refers to it as "deductive reasoning".
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In 1902 Peirce wrote that he now regarded the syllogistical forms and the doctrine of extension and comprehension (i.e., objects and characters as referenced by terms), as being less fundamental than he had earlier thought.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The hypothesis is framed, but not asserted, in a premise, then asserted as rationally suspectable in the conclusion.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Thus, as in the earlier categorical syllogistic form, the conclusion is formulated from some premise(s).
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] But all the same the hypothesis consists more clearly than ever in a new or outside idea beyond what is known or observed.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Induction in a sense goes beyond observations already reported in the premises, but it merely amplifies ideas already known to represent occurrences, or tests an idea supplied by hypothesis; either way it requires previous abductions in order to get such ideas in the first place.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Induction seeks facts to test a hypothesis; abduction seeks a hypothesis to account for facts.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Note that the hypothesis ("A") could be of a rule.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] It need not even be a rule strictly necessitating the surprising observation ("C"), which needs to follow only as a "matter of course"; or the "course" itself could amount to some known rule, merely alluded to, and also not necessarily a rule of strict necessity.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Peirce did not remain quite convinced about any such form as the categorical syllogistic form or the 1903 form.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In 1911, he wrote, "I do not, at present, feel quite convinced that any logical form can be assigned that will cover all 'Retroductions'.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] It is a method for fruitful clarification of conceptions by equating the meaning of a conception with the conceivable practical implications of its object's conceived effects.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Peirce held that that is precisely tailored to abduction's purpose in inquiry, the forming of an idea that could conceivably shape informed conduct.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In various writings in the 1900s he said that the conduct of abduction (or retroduction) is governed by considerations of economy, belonging in particular to the economics of research.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] He regarded economics as a normative science whose analytic portion might be part of logical methodeutic (that is, theory of inquiry).
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Logical critic, or logic proper, on validity or justifiability of inference, the conditions for true representation.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Critique of arguments in their various modes (deduction, induction, abduction).
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Methodeutic, or speculative rhetoric, on the conditions for determination of interpretations.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Methodology of inquiry in its interplay of modes.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Peirce had, from the start, seen the modes of inference as being coordinated together in scientific inquiry and, by the 1900s, held that hypothetical inference in particular is inadequately treated at the level of critique of arguments.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] To increase the assurance of a hypothetical conclusion, one needs to deduce implications about evidence to be found, predictions which induction can test through observation so as to evaluate the hypothesis.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] That is Peirce's outline of the scientific method of inquiry, as covered in his inquiry methodology, which includes pragmatism or, as he later called it, pragmaticism, the clarification of ideas in terms of their conceivable implications regarding informed practice.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Induction is inference through an *index* (a sign by factual connection); a sample is an index of the totality from which it is drawn.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Deduction is inference through a *symbol* (a sign by interpretive habit irrespective of resemblance or connection to its object).
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] At the critical level Peirce examined the forms of abductive arguments (as discussed above), and came to hold that the hypothesis should economize explanation for plausibility in terms of the feasible and natural.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In 1908 Peirce described this plausibility in some detail.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The phrase "inference to the best explanation" (not used by Peirce but often applied to hypothetical inference) is not always understood as referring to the most simple and natural hypotheses (such as those with the fewest assumptions).
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] However, in other senses of "best", such as "standing up best to tests", it is hard to know which is the best explanation to form, since one has not tested it yet.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Still, for Peirce, any justification of an abductive inference as "good" is not completed upon its formation as an argument (unlike with induction and deduction) and instead depends also on its methodological role and promise (such as its testability) in advancing inquiry.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Here, considerations such as probability, absent from the treatment of abduction at the critical level, come into play.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Peirce indicated that abductive reasoning is driven by the need for "economy in research"—the expected fact-based productivity of hypotheses, prior to deductive and inductive processes of verification.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] A key concept proposed by him in this regard is "uberty"—the expected fertility and pragmatic value of reasoning.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] This concept seems to be gaining support via association to the Free Energy Principle.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Gilbert Harman was a professor of philosophy at Princeton University.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Harman's 1965 account of the role of "inference to the best explanation" – inferring the existence of that which we need for the best explanation of observable phenomena – has been very influential.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Stephen Jay Gould, in answering the Omphalos hypothesis, claimed that only hypotheses that can be proved incorrect lie within the domain of science and only these hypotheses are good explanations of facts worth inferring to.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Applications in artificial intelligence include fault diagnosis, belief revision, and automated planning.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The most direct application of abduction is that of automatically detecting faults in systems: given a theory relating faults with their effects and a set of observed effects, abduction can be used to derive sets of faults that are likely to be the cause of the problem.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In medicine, abduction can be seen as a component of clinical evaluation and judgment.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The Internist-I diagnostic system, the first AI system that covered the field of Internal Medicine, used abductive reasoning to converge on the most likely causes of a set of patient symptoms that it acquired through an interactive dialog with an expert user.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Abduction can also be used to model automated planning.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Given a logical theory relating action occurrences with their effects (for example, a formula of the event calculus), the problem of finding a plan for reaching a state can be modeled as the problem of abducting a set of literals implying that the final state is the goal state.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In intelligence analysis, analysis of competing hypotheses and Bayesian networks, probabilistic abductive reasoning is used extensively.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Similarly in medical diagnosis and legal reasoning, the same methods are being used, although there have been many examples of errors, especially caused by the base rate fallacy and the prosecutor's fallacy.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Belief revision, the process of adapting beliefs in view of new information, is another field in which abduction has been applied.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The main problem of belief revision is that the new information may be inconsistent with the prior web of beliefs, while the result of the incorporation cannot be inconsistent.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The process of updating the web of beliefs can be done by the use of abduction: once an explanation for the observation has been found, integrating it does not generate inconsistency.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In 1992 Peter Gärdenfors presented a paper which contained a brief survey of the area of belief revision and its relation to updating of logical databases, and explores the relationship between belief revision and nonmonotonic logic.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] This use of abduction is not straightforward, as adding propositional formulae to other propositional formulae can only make inconsistencies worse.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Instead, abduction is done at the level of the ordering of preference of the possible worlds.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Preference models use fuzzy logic or utility models.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In the philosophy of science, abduction has been the key inference method to support scientific realism, and much of the debate about scientific realism is focused on whether abduction is an acceptable method of inference.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In historical linguistics, abduction during language acquisition is often taken to be an essential part of processes of language change such as reanalysis and analogy.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In applied linguistics research, abductive reasoning is starting to be used as an alternative explanation to inductive reasoning, in recognition of anticipated outcomes of qualitative inquiry playing a role in shaping the direction of analysis.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] It is defined as "The use of an unclear premise based on observations, pursuing theories to try to explain it" (Rose et al., 2020, p.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is used as the mechanism for getting from art to agency.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] That is, abduction can explain how works of art inspire a *sensus communis:* the commonly held views shared by members that characterize a given society.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is the answer to this conundrum because the tentative nature of the abduction concept (Peirce likened it to guessing) means that not only can it operate outside of any pre-existing framework, but moreover, it can actually intimate the existence of a framework.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] As Gell reasons in his analysis, the physical existence of the artwork prompts the viewer to perform an abduction that imbues the artwork with intentionality.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] A statue of a goddess, for example, in some senses actually becomes the goddess in the mind of the beholder; and represents not only the form of the deity but also her intentions (which are adduced from the feeling of her very presence).
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Therefore, through abduction, Gell claims that art can have the kind of agency that plants the seeds that grow into cultural myths.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] The power of agency is the power to motivate actions and inspire ultimately the shared understanding that characterizes any given society.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In formal methods, logic is used to specify and prove properties of computer programs.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] Abduction has been used in mechanized reasoning tools to increase the level of automation of the proof activity.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] It led to a program-proof startup company, which was acquired by Facebook, and the Infer program analysis tool, which led to thousands of bugs being prevented in industrial codebases.
[src:humanities/abductive-reasoning] In addition to inference of function preconditions, abduction has been used to automate inference of invariants for program loops, inference of specifications of unknown code, and in synthesis of the programs themselves.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The science of abnormal psychology studies two types of behaviors: adaptive and maladaptive behaviors.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Maladaptive behaviors suggest that some problem(s) exist and can also imply that the individual is vulnerable and unable to cope with environmental stress, leading to difficulties functioning in daily life across emotions, thinking, physical actions, and speech.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Adaptive behaviors are well-suited to the nature of people, their lifestyles and surroundings, and the people they communicate with, allowing them to understand each other.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Clinical psychology is the applied field of psychology that seeks to assess, understand, and treat psychological conditions in clinical practice.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The theoretical field known as *abnormal psychology* may form a backdrop to such work.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Still, clinical psychologists in the field are unlikely to use the term 'abnormal' in reference to their practice.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Psychopathology is a similar term to abnormal psychology, but may have more of an implication of an underlying pathology (disease process), which assumes the medical model of mental disturbance and as such, is a term more commonly used in the medical specialty known as psychiatry.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Hippocrates (460–377 BCE) hypothesized that the body and mind become unwell when the so-called humors, vital fluids in the body, become unbalanced.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The four temperaments theory posits four such humors: black bile, yellow bile, phlegm, and blood.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Each humor was associated with a particular temperament: too much phlegm causes a person to be fatigued, too much black bile causes melancholia, yellow bile causes a quick temper, and too much blood causes optimism, cheerfulness, and confidence.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The act of placing individuals with mental illness in a separate facility known as an asylum dates to 1547, when King Henry VIII of England established the St.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] This hospital, nicknamed Bedlam, was famous for its deplorable conditions.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Asylums remained popular throughout the Middle Ages and the Renaissance era.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] These early asylums often had miserable conditions.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Patients were seen as a "burden" to society, locked away and treated almost like beasts to be dealt with, rather than patients needing treatment.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] However, many of the patients received helpful medical treatment.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] There was scientific curiosity into abnormal behavior, although it was rarely investigated in the early asylums.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Inmates in these early asylums were often put on display for profit, as they were viewed as less than human.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The early asylums were basically modifications of the existing criminal institutions.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] In the late 18th century, the idea of humane treatment for patients gained favor due to the work of Philippe Pinel in France.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] He pushed for the idea that the patients should be treated with kindness, and not the cruelty inflicted on them, as if they were animals or criminals.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] His experimental ideas, such as removing the chains from the patients, were met with reluctance.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The experiments in kindness proved a great success, helping reform how mental institutions would be run.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Institutionalization would continue to improve throughout the 19th and 20th centuries, as a result of the work of many humanitarians such as Dorothea Dix and the mental hygiene movement, which promoted the physical well-being of people with mental health conditions.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] "Dix, more than any other figure in the nineteenth century, made people in America and virtually all of Europe aware that the insane were being subjected to incredible abuses." Through this movement, millions of dollars were raised to build new institutions to house the mentally ill.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Mental hospitals grew substantially in number during the 20th century as care for the mentally ill increased.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] By 1939, there were over 400,000 patients in state mental hospitals in the US.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Hospital stays were normally quite long for the patients, with some individuals being treated for many years.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] These hospitals, while better than the asylums of the past, still lacked the means to provide effective treatment for patients.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Even though the reform movement had occurred, patients were often still met with cruel and inhumane treatment.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Things began to change in 1946, when Mary Jane Ward published the influential novel *The Snake Pit*, which was adapted into a popular movie of the same name.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The book called attention to the conditions that people with a mental health condition faced, and helped to spark concern in the general public to create more humane mental health care in these overcrowded hospitals.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] That same year, the National Institute of Mental Health was also created, providing support for training hospital employees and research into patients' conditions.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] During this period, the Hill–Burton Act was also passed, a program that funded mental health hospitals.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Along with the Community Health Services Act of 1963, the Hill–Burton Acts helped create outpatient psychiatric clinics, inpatient general hospitals, and rehabilitation and community consultation centers.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] In the late twentieth century, however, many mental hospitals were closed in many countries.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] In England, for example, only 14 of the 130 psychiatric institutions established in the early 20th century remained open at the start of the 21st century.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Kennedy launched the community health movement in the United States as a "bold new approach" to mental health care, aimed at coordinating mental health services for citizens in mental health centers.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Over the span of 40 years, the United States saw about a 90 percent drop in the number of patients in psychiatric hospitals.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Deinstitutionalisation ended the long-term confinement of patients in isolating mental hospitals, which could and did cause long-term negative adaptations.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] For instance, institutionalizing people with schizophrenia worsens negative symptoms.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] However, the practice is sometimes criticised for a perceived rise in homelessness amongst people who were previously institutionalized, or are presumed to have been in the institution era.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] People have tried to explain and control abnormal behavior for thousands of years.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Historically, there have been three main approaches to abnormal behavior: the supernatural, biological, and psychological traditions.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Abnormal psychology revolves around two major paradigms for explaining mental disorders, the *psychological* paradigm and the *biological* paradigm.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The psychological paradigm focuses more on the humanistic, cognitive, and behavioral causes and effects of psychopathology.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The biological paradigm includes theories that focus more on physical factors, such as genetics and neurochemistry.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] In the first supernatural tradition, also known as the demonological method, abnormal behavior is attributed to agents outside the human body.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] According to this model, abnormal behaviors are caused by demons, aliens, or spirits, or the influences of the Moon, planets, and stars.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] During the Stone Age, trepanning was performed on those who had mental illness, to literally cut the evil spirits out of the victim's head.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Conversely, Ancient Chinese, Ancient Egyptians, and Hebrews believed that these were evil demons or spirits and advocated exorcism.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] By the time of the Greeks and Romans, mental illnesses were thought to be caused by an imbalance of the four humors, which led to treatments such as draining fluids from the brain.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] During the Medieval period, many Europeans believed that the power of witches, demons, and spirits caused abnormal behaviors.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] People with psychological disorders were thought to be possessed by evil spirits that had to be exorcised through religious rituals.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] If exorcism failed, some authorities advocated steps such as confinement, beating, and other types of torture to make the body uninhabitable to witches, demons, and spirits.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The belief that witches, demons, and spirits were responsible for abnormal behavior persisted into the 15th century.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Swiss alchemist, astrologer, and physician Paracelsus (1493–1541), on the other hand, rejected the idea that abnormal behaviors were caused by witches, demons, and spirits and suggested that the movements of the moon and stars influenced people's mind and behaviors.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Some people, especially in developing countries, as well as some followers of religious sects in developed countries, continue to believe that supernatural powers influence human behavior.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] In Western academia, the supernatural tradition has been largely replaced by the biological and psychological traditions.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Throughout history, societies have proposed several explanations for abnormal human behavior.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] In some hunter-gatherer societies, animists have believed that people exhibiting abnormal behavior are possessed by malevolent spirits.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] This idea has been associated with trepanation, the practice of cutting a hole into the individual's skull to release the malevolent spirits.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Although it has been difficult to define abnormal psychology, one definition includes characteristics such as statistical infrequency.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] A more formalized response to spiritual beliefs about abnormality is the practice of exorcism.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Performed by religious authorities, exorcism is thought of as another way to release evil spirits who cause pathological behavior within the person.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] In some instances, individuals exhibiting unusual thoughts or behaviors have been exiled from society, or worse.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Perceived witchcraft, for example, has been punished by death.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Two Catholic Inquisitors wrote the *Malleus Maleficarum* (Latin for "The Hammer Against Witches"), which many Inquisitors and witch-hunters used.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] It contained an early taxonomy of perceived deviant behavior and proposed guidelines for prosecuting deviant individuals.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] In the biological tradition, psychological disorders are attributed to biological causes.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] In the psychological tradition, disorders are attributed to faulty psychological development, and to social context.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The medical or biological perspective holds the belief that most or all abnormal behavior can be attributed to a medical factor; assuming all psychological disorders are diseases.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The Greek physician Hippocrates, considered the father of Western medicine, played a major role in the biological tradition.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Hippocrates and his associates wrote the Hippocratic Corpus between 450 and 350 BC, in which they suggested that abnormal behaviors can be treated like any other disease.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Hippocrates viewed the brain as the seat of consciousness, emotion, intelligence, and wisdom, and believed that disorders involving these functions would logically be located there.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] These ideas of Hippocrates and his associates were later adopted by Galen, the Roman physician.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Galen extended these ideas and developed a strong and influential school of thought within the biological tradition that extended well into the 18th century.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Kendra Cherry, MSEd, states: "The medical approach to abnormal psychology focuses on the biological causes of mental illness.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] This perspective emphasizes understanding the underlying cause of disorders, which might include genetic inheritance, related physical disorders, infections, and chemical imbalances.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] According to Sigmund Freud's structural model, the id, ego, and superego are three theoretical constructs that define the way an individual interacts with the external world, as well as responding to internal forces The Id represents the instinctual drives of an individual that remain unconscious.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The superego represents a person's conscience and their internalization of societal norms and morality.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Finally, the ego serves to realistically integrate the id's drives with the superego's prohibitions.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Lack of development in the superego, or an incoherently developed Superego within an individual, will result in thoughts and actions that are irrational and abnormal, contrary to the norms and beliefs of society.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Unconscious fears drive irrational beliefs and can result in abnormal behavior.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Rational emotive behavior therapy helps to drive irrational and maladaptive beliefs out of one's mind.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The term sociocultural refers to the various circles of influence on the individual, ranging from close friends and family to the institutions and policies of a country or the world as a whole.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Discriminations, whether based on social class, income, race and ethnicity, or gender, can influence the development of abnormal behaviour.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The number of different theoretical perspectives in the field of psychological abnormality has made it difficult to explain psychopathology properly.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The attempt to explain all mental disorders with the same theory leads to reductionism (explaining a disorder or other complex phenomena using only a single idea or perspective).
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Most mental disorders are composed of several factors, which is why one must take into account several theoretical perspectives when attempting to diagnose or explain a particular behavioral abnormality or mental disorder.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Explaining mental disorders with a combination of theoretical perspectives is known as multiple causality.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The diathesis–stress model emphasizes the importance of applying multiple causality to psychopathology, by stressing that both precipitating causes and predisposing causes cause disorders.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] A precipitating cause is an immediate trigger that instigates a person's action or behavior.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] A predisposing cause is an underlying factor that interacts with the immediate factors to result in a disorder.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Both causes play a key role in the development of a psychological disorder.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] For example, high neuroticism antedates most types of psychopathology.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] There is a wide range of mental disorders that are considered to be forms of Abnormal Psychology.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Schizophrenia can be described as a disorder that causes extreme loss of touch with reality.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The Psychotic nature of schizophrenia manifests itself through delusions, as well as auditory and visual hallucinations.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Schizophrenia is known to have a genetic etiology, as well as other biological components, such as brain disruptions in the prenatal development period.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) is characterized by high amounts of inattention and hyperactive impulsiveness.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Inattentive symptoms include not listening, careless errors, disorganization, losing personal belongings, becoming easily distracted, and forgetfulness.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Symptoms of hyperactive impulsiveness include fidgeting, talking excessively, and interrupting others.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Antisocial personality disorder is a cluster of personality traits that lead to specific outcomes and violate others' rights.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] These personality traits include callousness, deceitfulness, lack of remorse, apathy, manipulation of others, impulsiveness, and grandiosity.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Additional traits may include superficial charm, sexual promiscuity, and pathological lying.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Dissociative identity disorder (DID) involves one individual having multiple personalities.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Those with DID are described as having multiple selves that each have their own consciousness and awareness.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] DID has two main etiologies, which are the post-traumatic and socio-cognitive models.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The post-traumatic model states that DID is caused by inescapable past trauma, such as child abuse.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The child dissociates and forms alternate personalities as a coping mechanism in response to the current trauma.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Even when the trauma ends, the personalities continue to disrupt the person's life long-term.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The socio-cognitive model states that people implicitly act as if they have multiple personalities to align with cultural norms.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Those with social anxiety disorder (SAD) have a very intense fear of social situations.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] This fear stems from the belief that the person will be evaluated negatively or embarrass themselves.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] SAD is also considered to be one of the more disabling mental disorders.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Symptoms of this disorder include fear in most, if not all, social situations.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] SAD can develop after a traumatic and/or embarrassing experience has occurred while other people were observing the person.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Generalized anxiety disorder is characterized by a constant, chronic state of worry and anxiety that is related to a large variety of situations and is difficult to control.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Additional symptoms may include irritability, fatigue, concentration difficulties, and restlessness.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Individuals with specific phobias have an extreme fear and avoidance of various objects or situations.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Specifically, fears become phobias when there is excessive and unreasonable fear that is disproportionate to the culture that the individual is in.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Examples of specific phobias include, but are not limited to, phobias of school, blood, injury, needles, small animals, and heights.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) is described as physical and mental distress related to past traumatic experiences.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] PTSD can manifest a large variety of symptoms, including, but not limited to, nightmares, flashbacks, avoidance, and/or physiological reactions related to stimuli regarding the trauma, shame, guilt, anger, hypervigilance, and social withdrawal.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] PTSD symptoms can arise due to various experiences that involve actual or threatened violence, injury, or death.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Firsthand experience, witnessing, or learning about traumatic experiences can lead to the development of PTSD.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The DSM-5 is the manual that contains the most widely discussed and researched information on this topic.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Various conditions have been included in this manual and continue to be added to the DSM-5.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The causes of many of these diseases stem from genetic, biological, sociocultural, systemic, and biopsychosocial factors.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Various counseling theories support and help explain the findings related to each illness.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] In North America, this is the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of the American Psychiatric Association.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The current version of the book is known as the DSM-5.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] It lists a set of disorders and provides detailed descriptions of what constitutes a mental disorder.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The DSM-5 identifies three key elements that must be present to constitute a mental disorder.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The DSM-5 uses three main sections to organize its contents.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Section I includes the introduction, use, and basics of the DSM-5.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Section II includes diagnostic criteria and codes.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Section III includes emerging measures and models.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Section I of the DSM-5 briefly prefaces purpose, content, structure, and use.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] This includes basics, introductions, and cautionary statements for forensic use.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Information is also given about the revision and review processes as well as the DSM-5's goals to harmonize with the ICD-11.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] An explanation regarding the change from the previous multi-axial classification system to the current three-section system is also included here.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Section II of the DSM-5 contains a wide range of diagnostic criteria and codes used to establish and diagnose a vast array of abnormal psychological constructs.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] These categories are used to organize abnormal psychological concepts based on their similarities.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Section III of the DSM-5 contains the various methods and strategies that are used to make clinical decisions, understand culture, and explore emerging diagnoses.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The major international nosologic system for the classification of mental disorders is the International Classification of Diseases, 10th revision (ICD-10).
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The ICD-10 has been used by World Health Organization (WHO) Member States since 1994.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Chapter five covers some 300 mental and behavioral disorders.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The APA's DSM-IV has influenced Chapter 5 of ICD-10, and there is a great deal of concordance between the two.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Beginning in January 2022, the ICD-11 will replace the ICD-10 in WHO member states.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] WHO maintains free access to the ICD-10 Online.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The ICD-11 is the most recent version of the International Classification of Diseases.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The *Mental, behavioral, or Neurodevelopmental disorders section* highlights forms of abnormal psychology.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Psychologists may use different perspectives to gain a better understanding of abnormal psychology.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Some of them may concentrate on a single perspective.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] But professionals prefer to combine two or three perspectives to obtain meaningful information for better treatments.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Psychoanalytic theory is heavily based on the theory of the neurologist Sigmund Freud.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] These ideas often represented repressed emotions and memories from a patient's childhood in the patient's unconscious.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] According to psychoanalytic theory, these repressions cause the disturbances people experience in their daily lives, and by finding their source, one should be able to eliminate them.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] This is accomplished through a variety of methods, including free association, hypnosis, and insight.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The goal of these methods is to induce a catharsis, or emotional release, in the patient, which should indicate that the source of the problem has been tapped and can then be treated.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Freud's psychosexual stages also played a key role in this form of therapy, as he would often believe that the problems the patient was experiencing were due to them becoming stuck, or "fixated", in a particular stage.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Dreams also played a major role in this form of therapy, as Freud viewed dreams as a way to gain insight into the unconscious mind.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Patients were often asked to keep dream journals to bring in for discussion during the next therapy session.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] There are many potential problems associated with this style of therapy, including resistance to the repressed memory or feeling, and negative transference onto the therapist.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Psychoanalysis was carried on by many after Freud, including his daughter Anna Freud, and Jacques Lacan.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Many others have also elaborated on Freud's original theory and added their own take on defense mechanisms or dream analysis.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] While psychoanalysis has fallen out of favor to more modern forms of therapy, it is still used by some clinical psychologists to varying degrees.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Behavior therapy relies on the principles of behaviorism, such as involving classical and operant conditioning.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Behaviorism arose in the early 20th century, from the work of psychologists such as James Watson and B.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Behaviorism states that all behaviors humans do are because of a stimulus and reinforcement.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] While this reinforcement is normally for good behavior, it can also occur for maladaptive behavior.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] In this therapeutic view, the patient's maladaptive behavior has been reinforced, which will lead to its repetition.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The goal of the therapy is to reinforce less maladaptive behaviors so that, over time, these adaptive behaviors become the patient's primary ones.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Humanistic therapy aims to achieve self-actualization (Carl Rogers, 1961).
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] In this style of therapy, the therapist will focus on the patient themselves rather than on the patient's problem.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The goal of this therapy is, by treating the patient as "human", rather than "client", to get to the source of the problem and to resolve the problem effectively.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Humanistic therapy has been on the rise in recent years and is associated with numerous benefits.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] It is considered one of the core elements needed for therapeutic effectiveness and a significant contributor to the well-being of not only the patient but society as a whole.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Some say that all therapeutic approaches today draw on the humanistic approach in some way, and that humanistic therapy is the best way to treat a patient.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Humanistic therapy can be used on people of all ages; it is very popular among children in its variant known as "play therapy".
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Cognitive behavioural therapy (CBT) aims to influence thought and cognition (Beck, 1977).
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] This form of therapy relies on not only the components of behavioral therapy as mentioned before, but also the elements of cognitive psychology.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] This relies on not only the clients behavioral problems that could have arisen from conditioning, but also their negative schemas and distorted perceptions of the world around them.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] These negative schemas may cause distress in the patient's life; for example, they may lead to unrealistic expectations about how well they should perform at work or how they should look.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] When these expectations are not met, it will often result in maladaptive behaviors, such as depression, obsessive compulsions, and anxiety.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] With CBT, the goal is to change the schemas causing stress in the patient's life and replace them with more realistic ones.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Once the negative schemas have been replaced, this will hopefully lead to remission of the patient's symptoms.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] CBT is considered particularly effective in the treatment of depression and has even been used in recent years in group settings.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] It is felt that using CBT in a group setting aids in giving its members a sense of support and decreasing the likelihood of them dropping out of therapy before the treatment has had time to work properly.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] CBT is an effective treatment for many patients, even those who do not have diseases and disorders typically thought of as psychiatric ones.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] For example, patients with the disease multiple sclerosis have found a lot of help using CBT.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The treatment often helps the patients cope with the disorder they have and how they can adapt to their new lives without developing new problems, such as depression or negative schemas about themselves.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] According to RAND, therapies are difficult to provide to all patients in need.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] A lack of funding and understanding of symptoms provides a major roadblock that is not easily avoided.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Individual symptoms and responses to treatment vary, creating a disconnect among patients, society, and caregivers/professionals.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] In play therapy, the clinicians will "play" with their client, usually with toys or a tea party.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Playing is typical child behavior; therefore, playing with the therapist will come naturally to the child.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] While playing together, the clinician will ask the patient questions, and in this setting, they seem less intrusive, more therapeutic, and more like a normal conversation.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] This should help the patient identify their issues and disclose them to the therapist with less difficulty than they may experience in a traditional counseling setting.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Play therapy involves a therapist observing a child as the child plays with toys and interacts with their surrounding environment.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The therapist plays both an observational and an interactional role in the intervention.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] This process allows the child to enact their problems through play and speak more comfortably with the therapist.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Although somewhat controversial, due to data that suggests a lack of effectiveness in children older than 10 years old, play therapy is a valuable treatment.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] This therapy is particularly useful for younger children under 10 who are consciously aware of their environment.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Play therapy is important, given that many therapeutic interventions effective for adults are less effective for children.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Family systems therapies are based on the belief that children's problems stem from issues within the family.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Family systems therapy aims to improve relationships among multiple people within specific families through therapeutic intervention.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] For the best effect, it is recommended that the entire family be included in the therapy.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The treatments include family management skill development and child–parent attachment development.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] These interventions help to improve family functioning.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Family therapists can teach family management skills, including improving supervision and disciplinary practices and creating environments that foster positive interactions between parents and children.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Child–parent attachment development involves altering or creating relationships between parents and children, in attempts to create secure bases for the child, and to facilitate trust, independence, and positive perceptions of family relationships.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] We see these situations a lot more than we think, which makes some spectrums of abnormal psychology more normal and more common.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] These goals are often achieved by creating understanding regarding behaviors, creating opportunities for attachment, and increasing the family's ability to think about their history and relationships.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] One of the primary criticisms of the term "Abnormal Psychology" is its contribution to the stigmatization of individuals with mental health conditions.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] The label "abnormal" implies a deviation from a societal norm, which can reinforce negative stereotypes and social exclusion.
[src:humanities/abnormal-psychology] Critics argue that such language can lead to individuals feeling marginalized, perpetuating a sense of "otherness" and reinforcing the stigma associated with mental health issues.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] An **academic discipline** or **academic field** is a subdivision of knowledge that is taught and researched at the college or university level.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Disciplines are defined (in part) and recognized by the academic journals in which research is published, and the learned societies and academic departments or faculties within colleges and universities to which their practitioners belong.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Academic disciplines are conventionally divided into the humanities (including philosophy, languages, art and cultural studies), the natural sciences (such as physics, chemistry, and biology); and the formal sciences like mathematics and computer science.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] The social sciences are sometimes considered a fourth category.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] It is also known as a *field of study*, *field of inquiry*, *research field* and *branch of knowledge*.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] The different terms are used in different countries and fields.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Individuals associated with academic disciplines are commonly referred to as *experts* or *specialists*.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Others, who may have studied liberal arts or systems theory rather than concentrating in a specific academic discipline, are classified as *generalists*.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] For example, professionals may encounter trouble communicating across academic disciplines because of differences in jargon, concepts, or methodology.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Some researchers believe that academic disciplines may, in the future, be replaced by what is known as Mode 2 or "post-academic science", which involves the acquisition of cross-disciplinary knowledge through the collaboration of specialists from various academic disciplines.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] The University of Paris in 1231 consisted of four faculties:- Theology, Medicine, Canon Law and Arts.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Educational institutions originally used the term "discipline" to catalog and archive the new and expanding body of information produced by the scholarly community.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Disciplinary designations originated in German universities during the beginning of the nineteenth century.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] In the early twentieth century, new academic disciplines such as education and psychology were added.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] In the 1970s and 1980s, there was an explosion of new academic disciplines focusing on specific themes, such as media studies, women's studies, and Africana studies.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Many academic disciplines designed as preparation for careers and professions, such as nursing, hospitality management, and corrections, also emerged in the universities.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Finally, interdisciplinary scientific fields of study such as biochemistry and geophysics gained prominence as their contribution to knowledge became widely recognized.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Some new disciplines, such as public administration, can be found in more than one disciplinary setting; some public administration programs are associated with business schools (thus emphasizing management), while others are linked to political science (emphasizing policy analysis).
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] As the twentieth century approached, these designations were gradually adopted by other countries and became the accepted conventional subjects.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] However, these designations differed between various countries.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] In the twentieth century, the natural science disciplines included: physics, chemistry, biology, geology, and astronomy.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] The social science disciplines included: economics, politics, sociology, and psychology.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Prior to the twentieth century, categories were broad and general, which was expected due to the lack of interest in science at the time.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Most practitioners of science were amateurs and were referred to as "natural historians" and "natural philosophers"—labels that date back to Aristotle—instead of "scientists".
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Natural history referred to what we now call life sciences and natural philosophy referred to the current physical sciences.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Prior to the twentieth century, few opportunities existed for science as an occupation outside the educational system.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Higher education provided the institutional structure for scientific investigation, as well as economic support for research and teaching.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Soon, the volume of scientific information rapidly increased and researchers realized the importance of concentrating on smaller, narrower fields of scientific activity.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Because of this narrowing, scientific specializations emerged.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] As these specializations developed, modern scientific disciplines in universities also improved their sophistication.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Eventually, academia's identified disciplines became the foundations for scholars of specific specialized interests and expertise.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] An influential critique of the concept of academic disciplines came from Michel Foucault in his 1975 book, *Discipline and Punish*.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Communities of academic disciplines can be found outside academia within corporations, government agencies, and independent organizations, where they take the form of associations of professionals with common interests and specific knowledge.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Such communities include corporate think tanks, NASA, and IUPAC.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Communities such as these exist to benefit the organizations affiliated with them by providing specialized new ideas, research, and findings.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Nations at various developmental stages will find the need for different academic disciplines during different times of growth.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] A newly developing nation will likely prioritize government, political matters and engineering over those of the humanities, arts and social sciences.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] On the other hand, a well-developed nation may be capable of investing more in the arts and social sciences.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Communities of academic disciplines would contribute at varying levels of importance during different stages of development.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] These categories explain how the different academic disciplines interact with one another.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Multidisciplinary (or pluridisciplinary) knowledge is associated with more than one existing academic discipline or profession.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] A multidisciplinary community or project is made up of people from different academic disciplines and professions.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] One key question is how well the challenge can be decomposed into subparts, and then addressed via the distributed knowledge in the community.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] The lack of shared vocabulary between people and communication overhead can sometimes be an issue in these communities and projects.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] If challenges of a particular type need to be repeatedly addressed so that each one can be properly decomposed, a multidisciplinary community can be exceptionally efficient and effective.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] There are many examples of a particular idea appearing in different academic disciplines, all of which came about around the same time.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] One example of this scenario is the shift from the approach of focusing on sensory awareness of the whole, "an attention to the 'total field'", a "sense of the whole pattern, of form and function as a unity", an "integral idea of structure and configuration".
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] This has happened in art (in the form of cubism), physics, poetry, communication and educational theory.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] According to Marshall McLuhan, this paradigm shift was due to the passage from the era of mechanization, which brought sequentiality, to the era of the instant speed of electricity, which brought simultaneity.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Multidisciplinary approaches also encourage people to help shape the innovation of the future.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] The political dimensions of forming new multidisciplinary partnerships to solve the so-called societal Grand Challenges were presented in the Innovation Union and in the European Framework Programme, the Horizon 2020 operational overlay.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Innovation across academic disciplines is considered the pivotal foresight of the creation of new products, systems, and processes for the benefit of all societies' growth and wellbeing.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Regional examples such as Biopeople and industry-academia initiatives in translational medicine such as SHARE.ku.dk in Denmark provide evidence of the successful endeavour of multidisciplinary innovation and facilitation of the paradigm shift.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] In practice, transdisciplinary can be thought of as the union of all interdisciplinary efforts.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] While interdisciplinary teams may be creating new knowledge that lies between several existing disciplines, a transdisciplinary team is more holistic and seeks to relate all disciplines into a coherent whole.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Cross-disciplinary knowledge is that which explains aspects of one discipline in terms of another.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Common examples of cross-disciplinary approaches are studies of the physics of music or the politics of literature.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Bibliometrics can be used to map several issues in relation to disciplines, for example, the flow of ideas within and among disciplines (Lindholm-Romantschuk, 1998) or the existence of specific national traditions within disciplines.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] Scholarly impact and influence of one discipline on another may be understood by analyzing the flow of citations.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] The Bibliometrics approach is described as straightforward because it is based on simple counting.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] The method is also objective but the quantitative method may not be compatible with a qualitative assessment and therefore manipulated.
[src:humanities/academic-discipline] The number of citations is dependent on the number of persons working in the same domain instead of inherent quality or published result's originality.
[src:humanities/acrobatics] Acrobatic traditions are found in many cultures, and there is evidence that the earliest such traditions occurred thousands of years ago.
[src:humanities/acrobatics] 2000 BC contains depictions of acrobatic feats on the backs of bulls.
[src:humanities/acrobatics] Ancient Greeks practiced acrobatics, and the noble court displays of the European Middle Ages would often include acrobatic performances that included juggling.
[src:humanities/acrobatics] In China, acrobatics have been a part of the culture since the Tang dynasty (618–907).
[src:humanities/acrobatics] Acrobatics were part of village harvest festivals.
[src:humanities/acrobatics] During the Tang dynasty, acrobatics saw much the same sort of development as European acrobatics saw during the Middle Ages, with court displays during the 7th through 10th century dominating the practice.
[src:humanities/acrobatics] Acrobatics continues to be an important part of modern Chinese variety art.
[src:humanities/acrobatics] Though the term initially applied to tightrope walking, in the 19th century, a form of performance art including circus acts began to use the term as well.
[src:humanities/acrobatics] In the late 19th century, tumbling and other acrobatic and gymnastic activities became competitive sport in Europe.
[src:humanities/acrobatics] Acrobatics has often served as a subject for fine art.
[src:humanities/acrobatics] Examples of this are paintings such as *Acrobats at the Cirque Fernando (Francisca and Angelina Wartenberg)* by Impressionist Pierre-Auguste Renoir, which depicts two German acrobatic sisters, and *Acrobats in a Paris suburb* by Viktor Vasnetsov.
[src:humanities/acrobatics] A *trapeze* is a short horizontal bar hung by ropes or metal straps from a support.
[src:humanities/acrobatics] Trapeze acts may be static, spinning (rigged from a single point), swinging or flying, and may be performed solo, double, triple or as a group act.
[src:humanities/acting] Acting involves a broad range of skills, including a well-developed imagination, emotional facility, physical expressivity, vocal projection, clarity of speech, and the ability to interpret drama.
[src:humanities/acting] Acting also demands an ability to employ dialects, accents, improvisation, observation and emulation, mime, and stage combat.
[src:humanities/acting] Many actors train at length in specialist programs or colleges to develop these skills.
[src:humanities/acting] The vast majority of professional actors have gone through extensive training.
[src:humanities/acting] Actors and actresses will often have many instructors and teachers for a full range of training involving singing, scene-work, audition techniques, and acting for camera.
[src:humanities/acting] Most early sources in the West that examine the art of acting (Ancient Greek: ὑπόκρισις, *hypokrisis*) discuss it as part of rhetoric.
[src:humanities/acting] One of the first known actors was an ancient Greek called Thespis of Icaria in Athens.
[src:humanities/acting] Writing two centuries after the event, Aristotle in his *Poetics* (c.
[src:humanities/acting] 335 BCE) suggests that Thespis stepped out of the dithyrambic chorus and addressed it as a separate character.
[src:humanities/acting] Before Thespis, the chorus narrated (for example, "Dionysus did this, Dionysus said").
[src:humanities/acting] When Thespis stepped out from the chorus, he spoke as if he were the character (for example, "I am Dionysus, I did this").
[src:humanities/acting] To distinguish between these different modes of storytelling—enactment and narration—Aristotle uses the terms "mimesis" (via enactment) and "diegesis" (via narration).
[src:humanities/acting] From the Greek actor Thespis' name derives the word "thespian".
[src:humanities/acting] Conservatories and drama schools typically offer two- to four-year training on all aspects of acting.
[src:humanities/acting] Universities mostly offer three- to four-year programs, in which a student is often able to choose to focus on acting, whilst continuing to learn about other aspects of theatre.
[src:humanities/acting] Schools vary in their approach, but in North America the most popular method taught derives from the 'system' of Konstantin Stanislavski, which was developed and popularised in America as method acting by Lee Strasberg, Stella Adler, Sanford Meisner, and others.
[src:humanities/acting] Other approaches may include a more physically based orientation, such as that promoted by theatre practitioners as diverse as Anne Bogart, Jacques Lecoq, Jerzy Grotowski, or Vsevolod Meyerhold.
[src:humanities/acting] Classes may also include psychotechnique, mask work, physical theatre, improvisation, and acting for camera.
[src:humanities/acting] Regardless of a school's approach, students should expect intensive training in textual interpretation, voice, and movement.
[src:humanities/acting] Applications to drama programmes and conservatories usually involve extensive auditions.
[src:humanities/acting] Anybody over the age of 18 can usually apply.
[src:humanities/acting] Training may also start at a very young age.
[src:humanities/acting] Acting classes and professional schools targeted at under-18s are widespread.
[src:humanities/acting] These classes introduce young actors to different aspects of acting and theatre, including scene study.
[src:humanities/acting] Increased training and exposure to public speaking allows people to maintain a calmer and more relaxed physiology.
[src:humanities/acting] Measuring a public speaker's heart rate is perhaps one of the easiest ways to assess changes in stress, as heart rate increases with anxiety.
[src:humanities/acting] As actors increase their performances, heart rate and other signs of stress may decrease.
[src:humanities/acting] This is very important in training actors, as adaptive strategies gained from increased exposure to public speaking can regulate implicit and explicit anxiety.
[src:humanities/acting] By attending an institution that specializes in acting, the increased opportunity to act will lead to a more relaxed physiology and a decrease in stress and its effects on the body.
[src:humanities/acting] These effects can range from hormonal to cognitive health that can impact quality of life and performance.
[src:humanities/acting] Some classical forms of acting involve a substantial element of improvised performance.
[src:humanities/acting] Most notable is its use by the troupes of the *commedia dell'arte*, a form of masked comedy that originated in Italy.
[src:humanities/acting] Improvisation as an approach to acting formed an important part of the Russian theatre practitioner Konstantin Stanislavski's 'system' of actor training, which he developed from the 1910s onwards.
[src:humanities/acting] Late in 1910, the playwright Maxim Gorky invited Stanislavski to join him in Capri, where they discussed training and Stanislavski's emerging "grammar" of acting.
[src:humanities/acting] Stanislavski would develop this use of improvisation in his work with his First Studio of the Moscow Art Theatre.
[src:humanities/acting] Stanislavski's use was extended further in the approaches to acting developed by his students, Michael Chekhov and Maria Knebel.
[src:humanities/acting] In the United Kingdom, the use of improvisation was pioneered by Joan Littlewood from the 1930s onwards and, later, by Keith Johnstone and Clive Barker.
[src:humanities/acting] In the United States, it was promoted by Viola Spolin, after working with Neva Boyd at a Hull House in Chicago, Illinois (Spolin was Boyd's student from 1924 to 1927).
[src:humanities/acting] Like the British practitioners, Spolin felt that playing games was a useful means of training actors and helped to improve an actor's performance.
[src:humanities/acting] With improvisation, she argued, people may find expressive freedom, since they do not know how an improvised situation will turn out.
[src:humanities/acting] Improvisation demands an open mind in order to maintain spontaneity, rather than pre-planning a response.
[src:humanities/acting] A character is created by the actor, often without reference to a dramatic text, and a drama is developed out of the spontaneous interactions with other actors.
[src:humanities/acting] This approach to creating new drama has been developed most substantially by the British filmmaker Mike Leigh, in films such as *Secrets & Lies* (1996), *Vera Drake* (2004), *Another Year* (2010), and *Mr.
[src:humanities/acting] Improvisation is also used to cover up if an actor or actress makes a mistake.
[src:humanities/acting] Acting in front of an audience many times can cause "stage fright", a form of stress in which someone becomes anxious in front of an audience.
[src:humanities/acting] This is common among actors, especially new actors, and can cause symptoms such as increased heart rate, increased blood pressure, and sweating.
[src:humanities/acting] In a 2017 study on American university students, actors of various experience levels all showed similarly elevated heart rates throughout their performances; this agrees with previous studies on professional and amateur actors' heart rates.
[src:humanities/acting] While all actors experienced stress, causing elevated heart rate, the more experienced actors displayed less heart rate variability than the less experienced actors in the same play.
[src:humanities/acting] The more experienced actors experienced less stress while performing, and therefore had a smaller degree of variability than the less experienced, more stressed actors.
[src:humanities/acting] The more experienced an actor is, the more stable their heart rate will be while performing, but will still experience elevated heart rates.
[src:humanities/acting] The semiotics of acting involves a study of the ways in which aspects of a performance come to operate for its audience as signs.
[src:humanities/acting] This process largely involves the production of meaning, whereby elements of an actor's performance acquire significance, both within the broader context of the dramatic action and in the relations each establishes with the real world.
[src:humanities/acting] In his *The Theatre and its Double* (1938), Artaud compared this interaction to the way in which a snake charmer communicates with a snake, a process which he identified as "mimesis"—the same term that Aristotle in his *Poetics* (c.
[src:humanities/acting] 335 BCE) used to describe the mode in which drama communicates its story, by virtue of its embodiment by the actor enacting it, as distinct from "diegesis", or the way in which a narrator may describe it.
[src:humanities/acting] These "vibrations" passing from the actor to the audience may not necessarily precipitate into significant elements as such (that is, consciously perceived "meanings"), but rather may operate by means of the circulation of "affects".
[src:humanities/acting] The approach to acting adopted by other theatre practitioners involve varying degrees of concern with the semiotics of acting.
[src:humanities/acting] Konstantin Stanislavski, for example, addresses the ways in which an actor, building on what he calls the "experiencing" of a role, should also shape and adjust a performance in order to support the overall significance of the drama—a process that he calls establishing the "perspective of the role".
[src:humanities/acting] Eugenio Barba argues that actors ought not to concern themselves with the significance of their performance behaviour; this aspect is the responsibility, he claims, of the director, who weaves the signifying elements of an actor's performance into the director's dramaturgical "montage".
[src:humanities/acting] The theatre semiotician Patrice Pavis, alluding to the contrast between Stanislavski's 'system' and Brecht's demonstrating performer—and, beyond that, to Denis Diderot's foundational essay on the art of acting, *Paradox of the Actor* (c.
[src:humanities/acting] The conventions that govern acting in general are related to structured forms of play, which involve, in each specific experience, "rules of the game." This aspect was first explored by Johan Huizinga (in *Homo Ludens*, 1938) and Roger Caillois (in *Man, Play and Games*, 1958).
[src:humanities/acting] Caillois, for example, distinguishes four aspects of play relevant to acting: *mimesis* (simulation), *agon* (conflict or competition), *alea* (chance), and *ilinx* (vertigo, or "vertiginous psychological situations" involving the spectator's identification or catharsis).
[src:humanities/acting] Actors and actresses need to make a resume when applying for roles.
[src:humanities/acting] The acting resume is very different from a normal resume; it is generally shorter, with lists instead of paragraphs, and it should have a head shot on the back.
[src:humanities/acting] Sometimes, a resume also contains a short 30-second to 1-minute reel displaying the actor's abilities, so that the casting director can see previous performances, if any.
[src:humanities/acting] An actor's resume should list projects they have acted in before, such as plays, movies, or shows, as well as special skills and their contact information.
[src:humanities/acting] Auditioning is the act of performing either a monologue or sides (lines for one character) as sent by the casting director.
[src:humanities/acting] Auditioning entails showing the actor's skills to present themselves as a different person; it may be as brief as two minutes.
[src:humanities/acting] For theater auditions it can be longer than two minutes, or they may perform more than one monologue, as each casting director can have different requirements for actors.
[src:humanities/acting] Actors should go to auditions dressed for the part, to make it easier for the casting director to visualize them as the character.
[src:humanities/acting] For television or film they will have to undergo more than one audition.
[src:humanities/acting] Oftentimes actors are called into another audition at the last minute, and are sent the sides either that morning or the night before.
[src:humanities/acting] Auditioning can be a stressful part of acting, especially if one has not been trained to audition.
[src:humanities/acting] Rehearsal is a process in which actors prepare and practice a performance together with directors and technical staff.
[src:humanities/acting] Some actors continue to rehearse a scene throughout the run of a show in order to keep the scene fresh in their minds and exciting for the audience.
[src:humanities/acting] A critical audience with evaluative spectators is known to induce stress on actors during performance.
[src:humanities/acting] Depending on what an actor is doing, their heart rate will vary.
[src:humanities/acting] This is the body's way of responding to stress.
[src:humanities/acting] Prior to a show, one will see an increase in heart rate due to anxiety.
[src:humanities/acting] While performing an actor has an increased sense of exposure which will increase performance anxiety and the associated physiological arousal, such as heart rate.
[src:humanities/acting] Heart rates increases more during shows compared to rehearsals because of the increased pressure, which is because a performance has a potentially greater impact on an actor's career.
[src:humanities/acting] After the show a decrease in the heart rate due to the conclusion of the stress inducing activity can be seen.
[src:humanities/acting] Often the heart rate will return to normal after the show or performance is done; however, during the applause after the performance there is a rapid spike in heart rate.
[src:humanities/acting] This can be seen not only in actors but also with public speaking and musicians.
[src:humanities/acting] There is a correlation between heart-rate and stress when actors' are performing in front of an audience.
[src:humanities/acting] Actors claim that having an audience has no change in their stress level, but as soon as they come on stage their heart-rate rises quickly before they speak their first lines.
[src:humanities/acting] A 2017 study measuring actors' heart-rate during performance showed that individual heart-rates rose right before the performance began.
[src:humanities/acting] Length of monologues, experience levels, and actions done on stage were important factors in the study.
[src:humanities/acting] Heart-rate drops significantly at the end of a monologue, big action scene, or performance.
[src:humanities/acting] Acting has been shown to be an effective tool for reducing stress created by social anxiety.
[src:humanities/humanities] The humanities include the academic study of philosophy, religion, history, language arts (literature, writing, oratory, rhetoric, poetry, etc.), the performing arts (theater, music, dance, etc.), and the visual arts (painting, sculpture, photography, filmmaking, etc.).
[src:humanities/humanities] The word *humanities* comes from the Renaissance Latin phrase *studia humanitatis*, which translates to *study of humanity*.
[src:humanities/humanities] The *studia humanitatis* was a course of study comprising grammar, literature, rhetoric, history, and moral philosophy, primarily drawn from the study of Latin and Greek classics.
[src:humanities/humanities] Historically, the humanities have been distinguished from the social sciences by their methods and objectives.
[src:humanities/humanities] While both fields study human behavior and culture, the humanities adopt an idiographic approach (focusing on the unique and context-specific), emphasizing critical, interpretative, and speculative methods, often with an emphasis on historical context and subjective meaning.
[src:humanities/humanities] In contrast, the social sciences employ a nomothetic approach (seeking general laws and patterns) through empirical and quantitative analysis, a distinction first conceptualized by philosopher Wilhelm Windelband.
[src:humanities/humanities] This methodological distinction, however, is not absolute.
[src:humanities/humanities] The humanities have also been justified as fostering self-reflection, civic responsibility, and cultural continuity.
[src:humanities/humanities] Though debates persist about the practical utility of the humanities, proponents argue that their unique focus on meaning, creativity, and critical inquiry contributes both to individual enrichment and the public sphere.
[src:humanities/humanities] Classics, in the Western academic tradition, refers to the studies of the cultures of classical antiquity, namely Ancient Greek and Latin and the Ancient Greek and Roman cultures.
[src:humanities/humanities] Classical studies are considered one of the cornerstones of the humanities; however, their popularity declined during the 20th century.
[src:humanities/humanities] Nevertheless, the influence of classical ideas on many humanities disciplines, such as philosophy and literature, remains strong.
[src:humanities/humanities] History is systematically collected information about the past.
[src:humanities/humanities] When used as the name of a field of study, *history* refers to the study and interpretation of the record of humans, societies, institutions, and any topic that has changed over time.
[src:humanities/humanities] Traditionally, the study of history has been considered a part of the humanities.
[src:humanities/humanities] In modern academia, history can occasionally be classified as a social science, though this definition is contested.
[src:humanities/humanities] While the scientific study of language is known as linguistics and is generally considered a social science, a natural science or a cognitive science, the study of languages is also central to the humanities.
[src:humanities/humanities] Literature, covering a variety of uses of language including prose forms (such as the novel), poetry and drama, also lies at the heart of the modern humanities curriculum.
[src:humanities/humanities] College-level programs in a foreign language usually include the study of important works of literature in that language, as well as the language itself.
[src:humanities/humanities] In everyday language, law refers to a rule that is enforced by a governing institution, as opposed to a moral or ethical rule that is not subject to formal enforcement.
[src:humanities/humanities] The study of law can be seen as either a social science or a humanities discipline, depending on one's perspective.
[src:humanities/humanities] Some see it as a social science because of its objective and measurable nature, while others view it as a humanities discipline because of its focus on values and interpretation.
[src:humanities/humanities] Law is not always enforceable, especially in the context of international relations.
[src:humanities/humanities] Law has been defined in various ways, such as "a system of rules", "an interpretive concept" for achieving justice, "an authority" to mediate between people's interests, or "the command of a sovereign" backed by the threat of punishment.
[src:humanities/humanities] However one likes to think of law, it is a completely central social institution.
[src:humanities/humanities] The practical application of ideas from many social science and humanities disciplines, including philosophy, history, political science, economics, anthropology, and sociology, shapes legal policy.
[src:humanities/humanities] Law is politics, because politicians create it.
[src:humanities/humanities] Law is philosophy, because moral and ethical persuasions shape their ideas.
[src:humanities/humanities] Law tells many of history's stories, because statutes, case law, and codifications build up over time.
[src:humanities/humanities] Law is also economics, because any rule about contract, tort, property law, labour law, company law, and many more can have long-lasting effects on how productivity is organised and the distribution of wealth.
[src:humanities/humanities] The noun *law* derives from the Old English *word lagu*, meaning something laid down or fixed, and the adjective *legal* comes from the Latin word *LEX*.
[src:humanities/humanities] Philosophy—etymologically, the "love of wisdom"—is generally the study of problems concerning matters such as existence, knowledge, justification, truth, justice, right and wrong, beauty, validity, mind, and language.
[src:humanities/humanities] Philosophy is distinguished from other ways of addressing these issues by its critical, generally systematic approach and its reliance on reasoned argument, rather than on experiments (with experimental philosophy as an exception).
[src:humanities/humanities] Philosophy used to be a very broad term, encompassing what have since become separate disciplines, such as physics.
[src:humanities/humanities] (As Immanuel Kant noted, "Ancient Greek philosophy was divided into three sciences: physics, ethics, and logic.") Today, the main fields of philosophy are logic, ethics, metaphysics, and epistemology.
[src:humanities/humanities] Still, it overlaps with other disciplines.
[src:humanities/humanities] The field of semantics, for example, brings philosophy into contact with linguistics.
[src:humanities/humanities] This method of inquiry is largely indebted to the work of philosophers such as Gottlob Frege, Bertrand Russell, G.E.
[src:humanities/humanities] Based on current knowledge, it seems that all known cultures, both in the past and present, have some form of belief system or religious practice.
[src:humanities/humanities] While there may be isolated individuals or groups who do not practice any religion, it is unknown whether there has ever been a society entirely devoid of religious belief.
[src:humanities/humanities] The definition of religion is not universal, and different cultures may have different ideas about what constitutes religion.
[src:humanities/humanities] Religion may be characterized with a **community** since humans are social animals.
[src:humanities/humanities] **Rituals** are used to bound the community together.
[src:humanities/humanities] **Ethics** is a requirement of society, but not a requirement of religion.
[src:humanities/humanities] Shinto, Daoism, and other folk or natural religions do not have ethical codes.
[src:humanities/humanities] While some religions do include the concept of deities, others do not.
[src:humanities/humanities] Therefore, the supernatural does not necessarily require the existence of deities.
[src:humanities/humanities] Rather, it can be broadly defined as any phenomenon that cannot be explained by science or reason.
[src:humanities/humanities] **Magical thinking** creates explanations not available for empirical verification.
[src:humanities/humanities] **Stories** or myths are narratives being both didactic and entertaining.
[src:humanities/humanities] They are necessary for understanding the human predicament.
[src:humanities/humanities] Some other possible characteristics of religion are pollutions and purification, the sacred and the profane, sacred texts, religious institutions and organizations, and sacrifice and prayer.
[src:humanities/humanities] Some of the major problems that religions confront, and attempts to answer, are chaos, suffering, evil, and death.
[src:humanities/humanities] The non-founder religions are Hinduism, Shinto, and native or folk religions.
[src:humanities/humanities] Founder religions are Judaism, Christianity, Islam, Confucianism, Daoism, Mormonism, Jainism, Zoroastrianism, Buddhism, Sikhism, and the Baháʼí Faith.
[src:humanities/humanities] Religions must adapt over generations to remain relevant to their adherents.
[src:humanities/humanities] When traditional religions fail to address new concerns, then new religions will emerge.
[src:humanities/humanities] The performing arts differ from the visual arts in that the former uses the artist's own body, face, and presence as a medium.
[src:humanities/humanities] The latter uses materials such as clay, metal, or paint, which can be molded or transformed to create a work of art.
[src:humanities/humanities] Performing arts include acrobatics, comedy, dance, magic, music, opera, juggling, marching arts, such as brass bands, and theatre.
[src:humanities/humanities] Artists who participate in these arts in front of an audience are called performers, including actors, comedians, dancers, musicians, and singers.
[src:humanities/humanities] Performing arts are also supported by workers in related fields, such as songwriting and stagecraft.
[src:humanities/humanities] Performers often adapt their appearance, such as through costumes and stage makeup.
[src:humanities/humanities] There is also a specialized form of fine art in which the artists *perform* their work live to an audience.
[src:humanities/humanities] Most performance art also involves some form of plastic art, perhaps in the creation of props.
[src:humanities/humanities] Dance was often referred to as a *plastic art* during the Modern dance era.
[src:humanities/humanities] Musicology as an academic discipline can take several paths, including historical musicology, music literature, ethnomusicology, and music theory.
[src:humanities/humanities] Undergraduate music majors generally take courses in all of these areas, while graduate students focus on a particular path.
[src:humanities/humanities] In the liberal arts tradition, musicology is also used to broaden the skills of non-musicians by teaching them skills such as concentration and listening.
[src:humanities/humanities] Theatre (or theater) (Greek "theatron", *θέατρον*) is the branch of the performing arts concerned with acting out stories in front of an audience using combinations of speech, gesture, music, dance, sound and spectacle — indeed any one or more elements of the other performing arts.
[src:humanities/humanities] In addition to the standard narrative dialogue style, theatre takes such forms as opera, ballet, mime, kabuki, classical Indian dance, Chinese opera, mummers' plays, and pantomime.
[src:humanities/humanities] Dance (from Old French *dancier*, perhaps from Frankish) generally refers to human movement either used as a form of expression or presented in a social, spiritual or performance setting.
[src:humanities/humanities] Dance is also used to describe methods of non-verbal communication (see body language) between humans or animals (bee dance, mating dance), and motion in inanimate objects (*the leaves danced in the wind*).
[src:humanities/humanities] Choreography is the process of creating dances, and the people who create choreography are known as choreographers.
[src:humanities/humanities] Choreographers use movement, music, and other elements to create expressive and artistic dances.
[src:humanities/humanities] They may work alone or with other artists to create new works, and their work can be presented in a variety of settings, from small dance studios to large theaters.
[src:humanities/humanities] Definitions of what constitutes dance are dependent on social, cultural, aesthetic, artistic, and moral constraints and range from functional movement (such as Folk dance) to codified, virtuoso techniques such as ballet.
[src:humanities/humanities] The great traditions in art have a foundation in the art of one of the ancient civilizations, such as Ancient Japan, Greece and Rome, China, India, Greater Nepal, Mesopotamia and Mesoamerica.
[src:humanities/humanities] Ancient Greek art saw a veneration of the human physical form and the development of equivalent skills to show musculature, poise, beauty, and anatomically correct proportions.
[src:humanities/humanities] Ancient Roman art depicted gods as idealized humans, shown with characteristic distinguishing features (e.g., Zeus' thunderbolt).
[src:humanities/humanities] The emphasis on spiritual and religious themes in Byzantine and Gothic art of the Middle Ages reflected the church's dominance.
[src:humanities/humanities] However, in the Renaissance, a renewed focus on the physical world was reflected in art forms that depicted the human body and landscape in a more naturalistic, three-dimensional manner.
[src:humanities/humanities] Eastern art has generally worked in a style akin to Western medieval art, namely a concentration on surface patterning and local colour (meaning the plain colour of an object, such as basic red for a red robe, rather than the modulations of that colour brought about by light, shade and reflection).
[src:humanities/humanities] A characteristic of this style is that the local colour is often defined by an outline (a contemporary equivalent is the cartoon).
[src:humanities/humanities] This is evident, for example, in the art of India, Tibet, and Japan.
[src:humanities/humanities] Religious Islamic art forbids iconography, and expresses religious ideas through geometry instead.
[src:humanities/humanities] The physical and rational certainties depicted by the 19th-century Enlightenment were shattered not only by discoveries of relativity by Einstein and of unseen psychology by Freud, but also by unprecedented technological development.
[src:humanities/humanities] Increasing global interaction during this time led to a comparable influence of other cultures on Western art.
[src:humanities/humanities] Drawing is a means of making a picture, using a wide variety of tools and techniques.
[src:humanities/humanities] It generally involves making marks on a surface by applying pressure with a tool or moving it across the surface.
[src:humanities/humanities] Common tools are graphite pencils, pen and ink, inked brushes, wax color pencils, crayons, charcoals, pastels, and markers.
[src:humanities/humanities] Digital tools that simulate these effects are also used.
[src:humanities/humanities] The main techniques used in drawing are: line drawing, hatching, crosshatching, random hatching, scribbling, stippling, and blending.
[src:humanities/humanities] A computer-aided designer who excels in technical drawing is referred to as a *draftsman* or *draughtsman*.
[src:humanities/humanities] Literally, painting is the practice of applying pigment suspended in a carrier (or medium) and a binding agent (a glue) to a surface (support) such as paper, canvas or a wall.
[src:humanities/humanities] However, when used in an artistic sense, it means the use of this activity in combination with drawing, composition, and other aesthetic considerations to manifest the expressive and conceptual intention of the practitioner.
[src:humanities/humanities] Painting has been used throughout history to express spiritual and religious ideas, from mythological scenes on pottery to the frescoes of the Sistine Chapel, to body art.
[src:humanities/humanities] Colour is highly subjective but has observable psychological effects that can differ from one culture to the next.
[src:humanities/humanities] Black is associated with mourning in the West, but elsewhere, white may be.
[src:humanities/humanities] Some painters, theoreticians, writers and scientists, including Goethe, Kandinsky, Isaac Newton, have written their own colour theories.
[src:humanities/humanities] Moreover, the use of language is only a generalization for a colour equivalent.
[src:humanities/humanities] The word "red", for example, can cover a wide range of variations on the pure red of the spectrum.
[src:humanities/humanities] Unlike music, where notes such as C or C# are universally accepted, there is no formalized register of colors.
[src:humanities/humanities] However, the Pantone system is widely used in the printing and design industry to standardize color reproduction.
[src:humanities/humanities] Modern artists have extended the practice of painting considerably to include, for example, collage.
[src:humanities/humanities] This began with cubism and is not painting in a strict sense.
[src:humanities/humanities] Some modern painters incorporate different materials such as sand, cement, straw or wood for their texture.
[src:humanities/humanities] Examples of these are the works of Jean Dubuffet or Anselm Kiefer.
[src:humanities/humanities] Sculpture involves creating three-dimensional forms out of various materials.
[src:humanities/humanities] These typically include malleable substances like clay and metal, but may also extend to materials that are cut or shaved into the desired form, such as stone and wood.
[src:humanities/humanities] In the West, the history of the humanities can be traced to ancient Greece, where they formed the basis of a broad education for citizens.
[src:humanities/humanities] During Roman times, the concept of the seven liberal arts evolved, involving grammar, rhetoric and logic (the trivium), along with arithmetic, geometry, astronomy and music (the quadrivium).
[src:humanities/humanities] These subjects formed the bulk of medieval education, with the emphasis being on the humanities as skills or "ways of doing".
[src:humanities/humanities] A major shift occurred with the Renaissance humanism of the fifteenth century, when the humanities began to be regarded as subjects to study rather than practice, with a corresponding shift away from traditional fields into areas such as literature and history (*studia humaniora*).
[src:humanities/humanities] In the 20th century, this view was in turn challenged by the postmodernist movement, which sought to redefine the humanities in more egalitarian terms suitable for a democratic society since the Greek and Roman societies in which the humanities originated were elitist and aristocratic.
[src:humanities/humanities] A distinction is usually drawn between the social sciences and the humanities.
[src:humanities/humanities] For many decades, there has been a growing public perception that a humanities education inadequately prepares graduates for employment.
[src:humanities/humanities] The common belief is that graduates from such programs face underemployment and that incomes are too low for a humanities education to be worth the investment.
[src:humanities/humanities] Humanities graduates find employment in a wide variety of management and professional occupations.
[src:humanities/humanities] Many humanities graduates may find themselves with no specific career goals upon graduation, which can lead to lower incomes in the early stages of their careers.
[src:humanities/humanities] On the other hand, graduates from more career-oriented programs often find jobs more quickly.
[src:humanities/humanities] However, the long-term career prospects of humanities graduates may be similar to those of other graduates, as research shows that by five years after graduation, they generally find a career path that appeals to them.
[src:humanities/humanities] There is empirical evidence that graduates from humanities programs earn less than graduates from other university programs.
[src:humanities/humanities] However, the empirical evidence also shows that humanities graduates still earn notably higher incomes than workers with no postsecondary education, and have job satisfaction levels comparable to their peers from other fields.
[src:humanities/humanities] Humanities graduates also earn more as their careers progress; ten years after graduation, the income difference between humanities graduates and graduates from other university programs is no longer statistically significant.
[src:humanities/humanities] Humanities graduates can boost their incomes if they obtain advanced or professional degrees.
[src:humanities/humanities] Humanities majors are sought after in many areas of business, specifically for their critical thinking and problem-solving skills.
[src:humanities/humanities] Research has shown that humanities majors are especially adept at "soft skills" such as "written and oral communication, creative problem-solving, teamwork, decision-making, self-management, and critical analysis".
[src:humanities/humanities] Modeled after the National Science Board's Science and Engineering Indicators, Humanities Indicators are a source of reliable benchmarks to guide analysis of the state of the humanities in the United States.
[src:humanities/humanities] The Commission on the Humanities and Social Sciences 2013 report, "The Heart of the Matter", supports the notion of a broad "liberal arts education" that includes study in disciplines ranging from the natural sciences to the arts and the humanities.
[src:humanities/humanities] Many colleges provide such an education; some require it.
[src:humanities/humanities] The University of Chicago and Columbia University were among the first schools to require an extensive core curriculum in philosophy, literature, and the arts for all students.
[src:humanities/humanities] Other colleges with nationally recognized, mandatory programs in the liberal arts are Fordham University, St.
[src:humanities/humanities] John's College, Saint Anselm College and Providence College.
[src:humanities/humanities] Prominent proponents of liberal arts in the United States have included Mortimer J.
[src:humanities/humanities] In 1950, 1.2% of Americans aged 22 had earned a degree in the humanities.
[src:humanities/humanities] This represents a doubling of the number of Americans with degrees in the humanities over a 60-year period.
[src:humanities/humanities] The increase in the number of Americans with humanities degrees is in part due to the overall rise in college enrollment in the United States.
[src:humanities/humanities] In 1940, 4.6% of Americans had a four-year degree, but by 2016, this figure had risen to 33.4%.
[src:humanities/humanities] This means that the total number of Americans with college degrees has increased significantly, resulting in a greater number of people with degrees in the humanities as well.
[src:humanities/humanities] The proportion of degrees awarded in the humanities has declined in recent decades, even as the overall number of people with humanities degrees has increased.
[src:humanities/humanities] In 1954, 36% of Harvard undergraduates majored in the humanities, but in 2012, only 20% did so.
[src:humanities/humanities] As recently as 1993, the humanities accounted for 15% of the bachelor's degrees awarded by colleges and universities in the United States.
[src:humanities/humanities] As of 2022, they accounted for less than 9%.
[src:humanities/humanities] Researchers in the humanities have developed numerous large- and small-scale digital corporations, such as digitized collections of historical texts, along with digital tools and methods for analyzing them.
[src:humanities/humanities] Their aim is both to uncover new knowledge about corpora and to visualize research data in new and revealing ways.
[src:humanities/humanities] Much of this activity occurs in a field called the digital humanities.
[src:humanities/humanities] Politicians in the United States currently espouse a need for increased funding of the STEM fields, science, technology, engineering, and mathematics.
[src:humanities/humanities] Federal funding represents a much smaller fraction of funding for the humanities than other fields, such as STEM or medicine.
[src:humanities/humanities] The result was a decline in quality in both college and pre-college education in the humanities field.
[src:humanities/humanities] The contemporary debate in the field of critical university studies centers around the declining value of the humanities.
[src:humanities/humanities] As in America, there is a perceived decline in interest within higher education policy in research that is qualitative and does not produce marketable products.
[src:humanities/humanities] This threat can be seen in a variety of forms across Europe, but much critical attention has been paid to research assessment in particular.
[src:humanities/humanities] For example, the UK [Research Excellence Framework] has been subject to criticism due to its assessment criteria from across the humanities and, indeed, the social sciences.
[src:humanities/humanities] In particular, the notion of "impact" has generated significant debate.
[src:humanities/humanities] Since the late 19th century, a central justification for the humanities has been that they aid and encourage self-reflection—a self-reflection that, in turn, helps develop personal consciousness or an active sense of civic duty.
[src:humanities/humanities] Wilhelm Dilthey and Hans-Georg Gadamer centered the humanities' attempt to distinguish itself from the natural sciences in humankind's urge to understand its own experiences.
[src:humanities/humanities] This understanding, they claimed, ties like-minded people from similar cultural backgrounds together and provides a sense of cultural continuity with the philosophical past.
[src:humanities/humanities] Scholars in the late 20th and early 21st centuries extended that "narrative imagination" to the ability to understand the records of lived experiences outside of one's own individual social and cultural context.
[src:humanities/humanities] Through that narrative imagination, it is claimed, humanities scholars and students develop a conscience more suited to the multicultural world we live in.
[src:humanities/humanities] That conscience might take the form of a passive one that allows more effective self-reflection or extend into active empathy that facilitates the dispensation of civic duties a responsible world citizen must engage in.
[src:humanities/humanities] There is disagreement, however, on the level of influence humanities study can have on an individual and whether or not the understanding produced in humanistic enterprise can guarantee an "identifiable positive effect on people".
[src:humanities/humanities] There are three major branches of knowledge: natural sciences, social sciences, and the humanities.
[src:humanities/humanities] Technology is the practical extension of the natural sciences, as politics is the extension of the social sciences.
[src:humanities/humanities] Technology, politics, and culturonics are designed to transform what their respective disciplines study: nature, society, and culture.
[src:humanities/humanities] The divide between humanistic study and the natural sciences also informs arguments about meaning in the humanities.
[src:humanities/humanities] What distinguishes the humanities from the natural sciences is not a certain subject matter, but rather the mode of approach to any question.
[src:humanities/humanities] The humanities focus on understanding meaning, purpose, and goals, and further the appreciation of singular historical and social phenomena—an interpretive method of finding "truth"—rather than explaining the causality of events or uncovering the truth of the natural world.
[src:humanities/humanities] Apart from its societal application, narrative imagination is an important tool in the (re)production of understood meaning in history, culture, and literature.
[src:humanities/humanities] Imagination, as part of the toolkit of artists or scholars, helps create meaning that invokes a response from an audience.
[src:humanities/humanities] Since a humanities scholar is always within the nexus of lived experiences, no "absolute" knowledge is theoretically possible; knowledge is instead a ceaseless procedure of inventing and reinventing the context a text is read in.
[src:humanities/humanities] Poststructuralism has problematized an approach to the humanistic study based on questions of meaning, intentionality, and authorship.
[src:humanities/humanities] In the wake of the death of the author proclaimed by Roland Barthes, various theoretical currents such as deconstruction and discourse analysis seek to expose the ideologies and rhetoric operative in producing both the purportedly meaningful objects and the hermeneutic subjects of humanistic study.
[src:humanities/humanities] This exposure has opened up the interpretive structures of the humanities to criticism that humanities scholarship is "unscientific" and therefore unfit for inclusion in modern university curricula because of the very nature of its changing contextual meaning.
[src:humanities/humanities] Some, like Stanley Fish, have claimed that the humanities can defend themselves best by refusing to make any claims of utility.
[src:humanities/humanities] Furthermore, critical thinking, while arguably a result of humanistic training, can be acquired in other contexts.
[src:humanities/humanities] And the humanities do not even provide any more the kind of social cachet (what sociologists sometimes call "cultural capital") that was helpful to succeed in Western society before the age of mass education following World War II.
[src:humanities/humanities] Instead, scholars like Fish suggest that the humanities offer a unique kind of pleasure, a pleasure based on the common pursuit of knowledge (even if it is only disciplinary knowledge).
[src:humanities/humanities] In this argument, then, only the academic pursuit of pleasure can provide a link between the private and the public realm in modern Western consumer society and strengthen that public sphere that, according to many theorists, is the foundation for modern democracy.
[src:humanities/humanities] The result is that professors and their students adhere rigidly to a limited set of viewpoints and have little interest in or understanding of opposing viewpoints.
[src:humanities/humanities] Once they obtain this intellectual self-satisfaction, persistent lapses in learning, research, and evaluation are common.
[src:humanities/humanities] Implicit in many of these arguments supporting the humanities are the makings of arguments against public support of the humanities.
[src:humanities/humanities] Joseph Carroll asserts that we live in a changing world, a world where "cultural capital" is replaced with *scientific literacy*, and in which the romantic notion of a Renaissance humanities scholar is obsolete.
[src:humanities/humanities] Despite many humanities-based arguments against the humanities, some within the exact sciences have called for their return.
[src:humanities/humanities] In 2017, Science popularizer Bill Nye retracted previous claims about the supposed 'uselessness' of philosophy.
[src:humanities/humanities] As Bill Nye states, "People allude to Socrates and Plato and Aristotle all the time, and I think many of us who make those references don't have a solid grounding," he said.
[src:humanities/humanities] "It's good to know the history of philosophy." Scholars, such as biologist Scott F.
[src:humanities/humanities] Gilbert, make the claim that it is in fact the increasing predominance, leading to exclusivity, of scientific ways of thinking that need to be tempered by historical and social context.
[src:humanities/humanities] Gilbert worries that the commercialization inherent in some ways of conceiving of science (the pursuit of funding, academic prestige, etc.) needs to be examined from the outside.
